  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements aimed at preventing money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- Established global standards for combating money laundering\n- Sets recommendations for national legal and regulatory systems\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention Against Corruption\n\n3. Basel Committee Guidelines\n- Provides banking supervision standards to prevent financial crimes\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF) regulations\n- Helps countries develop anti-money laundering frameworks\n\n5. Basel III Accord\n- Includes provisions to strengthen financial system transparency\n\nMost countries have national laws implementing these international standards, requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nThe goal is to detect and prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.\n\nThese laws apply to various financial sectors including banking, securities, insurance, and money transfer services.\n\nPenalties for non-compliance can include significant fines and potential criminal charges.",
